pull_request.title: Clear session from storage if no recaller can be found
pull_request.body:
Hello!

So, if somehow in your application you delete the authenticatable (lets say from the users table) without clearing the session and the user still has the cookie, because of 
` if (! is_null($id) && $this->user = $this->provider->retrieveById($id)) {
            $this->fireAuthenticatedEvent($this->user);
}`

Every @can directive every Auth check (anything that uses the Auth::user) will cause for a db query spamming the database since the user is never set. On top of that if you do any auth checks in your application with Auth::id() it doesn't return null because of
`return $this->user()
                    ? $this->user()->getAuthIdentifier()
                    : $this->session->get($this->getName());`

Which is kind of a security issue. Not sure if it is only in my codebase but I thought it would be safer to open this PR to make you aware of the issue!

Thanks for your time

pull_request.title: [11.x] Efficient and Flexible Execution of Redis Lua Scripts
pull_request.body:
### Summary

This PR introduces new classes that offer improved handling of Redis Lua scripts, providing greater flexibility and control over script arguments and keys. These enhancements allow for easier execution of Redis Lua scripts with several benefits.

### Benefits of this

Some of the benefits of this PR include:

- Easy specification of keys and arguments to be passed to a script
- Option to enable or disable Redis Lua script caching
- Custom exception class called LuaScriptLoadException for better handling of Lua script errors
- Enhanced efficiency and flexibility of executing Redis Lua scripts, making it ideal for Redis-powered applications

### Reasons for the Changes

The changes in this PR provide an intuitive and efficient way to work with Redis Lua scripts. This is particularly useful for developers working with Redis in complex or high-performance applications. The new class also helps to minimize the network overhead associated with loading and executing Lua scripts in Redis, which can have a significant impact on application performance and latency.

### Strategy

The strategy for this Pull Request is to optimize success by prioritizing speed. To achieve this, we utilized `EVALSHA` by inputting the sha1 hash of the script provided. Initially, an error occurred because the script had not been loaded into Redis. However, we resolved this issue by loading the script into the server and subsequently re-invoking EVALSHA without any further errors.
It's important to note that the Redis script cache is always volatile. The cache may be cleared when the server restarts, during fail-over when a replica assumes the master role, or explicitly by [SCRIPT FLUSH](https://redis.io/commands/script-flush). That means that cached scripts are ephemeral, and the cache's contents can be lost at any time. [Ref](https://redis.io/docs/manual/programmability/eval-intro/#cache-volatility)

### Example usage
```php
use Illuminate\Redis\Lua\LuaScript;
use Illuminate\Redis\Lua\LuaScriptArguments;
use Illuminate\Redis\Lua\LuaScriptExecutor;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Redis;

$luaScript = <<<'LUA'
return redis.call("incr", KEYS[1])
LUA;

LuaScriptExecutor::create(Redis::connection())
            ->execute(LuaScript::fromPlainScript($luaScript), LuaScriptArguments::withKeys("key1"));

// Or if we want to integrate this with the Redis facade
Redis::connection()->lua()
            ->execute(LuaScript::fromPlainScript($luaScript), LuaScriptArguments::withKeys("key1"));
```

#### Checklist

- [x] Added new classes with relevant features. 
- [x] Added unit tests
- [x] Integrate with other components that used Redis Lua scripting feature

pull_request.title: [10.x] Fixes usage with `sqlsrv` databases
pull_request.body:
Scout is currently experiencing compatibility issues with  Microsoft SQL Server databases, as an error is thrown when attempting to import models on Scout. The error message is as follows:

```
  SQLSTATE[HY000]: General error: 20018 A column has been specified more than once in the order by list. Columns in the order by list must be unique. [20018] (severity 15) [select top 500 * from [users] order by [users].[id] asc, [id] asc] (Connection: sqlsrv, SQL: select top 500 * from [users] order by [users].[id] asc, [id] asc)
  ```
  
The regression was introduced in the changes made during the pull request at https://github.com/laravel/scout/pull/509. It happens because two "order by" statements are used with the same column name. While this doesn't pose any problems with other database drivers, it causes issues with Microsoft SQL Server databases, as they do not allow multiple "order by" clauses with the same column name.

Fixes https://github.com/laravel/scout/issues/723.

pull_request.title: Change example nginx document root path
pull_request.body: On systems where SELinux is enabled, files placed into the previous example nginx root path would be blocked from being read by nginx. This update provides an example path that would work on these systems because `/srv/www/*` is in the default SELinux fcontext ruleset.
